My guest and I decided to try Brewer’s Tap and Table. The appetizers initially seemed ok- oysters (will never eat this again) and burrata cheese. The entrees were mediocre- I had duck and it was chewy/underdone in some places. As we waited for our second drinks my guest immediately felt ill and ended up getting sick in the restaurant. We left without finishing our meals or drinks. I then started to feel ill within 30 min of leaving the restaurant. We both were sick until the next morning. I notified the restaurant and they said they were sorry and that no one else was sick that night. Disappointed that we spent about $150 and didn’t finish our meals/drinks. Surprised we were not offered some sort of reimbursement for leaving untouched parts of our meal on the table. Also believe this was too much of coincidence that we both became sick during the same meal (we had not eaten/spent any time together prior to dinner). Hard time thinking about this food without feeling nauseas. Too bad because would be nice to have another Moody Street dinner option.

(1.5 stars, edited to include more info) Came here on a Saturday night for a friend's birthday. We were a group of 20, so we already expected it to take a while for everyone to order, for everyone to get food, etc, but we made a reservation for dinner ahead of time. So what we did not expect was for them to seat the majority of the group in what looked like their lounge/waiting area, full of couches and 2 low tables. A few members of the group sat at the end of the bar. It did take a while to get drinks and food, as expected, but when they did come out, the waitresses practically shouted our orders at us as my friend said, "like an auction". A bunch of people in the group were skipped over, so their orders never got taken, it took a while to put their orders in and, consequently, they got their food much later. One of my friends also had her drink order taken, and then when everyone else's drinks came out, she was told that there was no more rosé, which seems like something a waiter should check before confirming the order. And the group in the lounge area- like no one should be expected to eat with their food on their lap in a nice restaurant. A table shouldn't be too much to ask for. And keep in mind, the restaurant wasn't completely full. We also saw that there was an upstairs area (not sure if you had to specially reserve it, but at least it seemed like it would have been a much better place to seat 20 people). They also had a small separated dining room, which became free before we got our food. The lounge group asked to be moved there, but we weren't allowed. Yes, we are college students, but we were dressed nicely, we weren't being loud, and we're still paying customers. And we were here for a birthday, the birthday girl should not have to worry about where her friends are going to eat their dinner. I split the grilled cheese and calamari appetizer with a friend. The food was pretty good, which was the only saving grace of the night and the only reason this review isn't one star.

My wife and I sat at the bar on a Saturday evening. Service was excellent and we never felt ignored. You can make your own beer flight using any of the beers on tap. I had the Cuban sandwich which may have been the best sandwich I've ever had. It was served on a roll that was inside-out, which I have never seen before and enjoyed. The French fries had a smoky flavor that we loved. My wife got the burger, which was cooked perfectly - a thin layer on the outside was deliciously charred and the entire interior was a uniform pink. Most places give you a burger that is varying levels of grey with a pink dot in the middle. I've only ever had one other burger cooked this expertly and it was on our honeymoon in Napa. In summary, this is not your average tap house - the beers are great, but the food is a level beyond with attention to detail that is usually only seen in finer dining. Kudos to the chef. We will definitely be back!
